{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17660007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17660007"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:19:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22641"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22641"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15588"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111071"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15588","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15588"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22641"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93192"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"763"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45142"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111071"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-year history of a swelling in the left groin. The swelling has not bothered him much until recently when it started to increase in size. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The swelling is clearly evident when the patient stands up and extends from the groin into the scrotum (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hydrocele","Femoral hernia","Inguinoscrotal hernia","Lipoma","Varicocele"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a long-standing groin swelling that has recently increased in size and extends into the scrotum when standing. The location, chronicity, and behaviour of the swelling are characteristic of an inguinoscrotal hernia. Inguinal hernias are common in elderly men and can progressively enlarge over time. When an indirect inguinal hernia becomes sufficiently large, it can traverse the entire inguinal canal and descend into the scrotum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInguinoscrotal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. These hernias originate from the deep inguinal ring, travel along the inguinal canal, exit through the superficial inguinal ring, and descend into the scrotum. The four-year history suggests a gradually enlarging indirect inguinal hernia that has now become inguinoscrotal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydrocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a collection of fluid within the tunica vaginalis surrounding the testis. While hydroceles can occasionally extend into the inguinal canal (communicating hydrocele), they typically present as scrotal swelling rather than groin swelling, and extension from the groin into the scrotum would be very unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral hernia\u003C/strong\u003E protrudes through the femoral canal below the inguinal ligament. Due to the anatomical constraints and direction of the femoral canal, these hernias extend inferiorly along the upper thigh rather than into the scrotum. They are also more common in women than men.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELipoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign fatty tumour that could theoretically occur in the groin. However, a lipoma extending from the groin into the scrotum would be extremely unusual, and lipomas do not typically change in prominence with standing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricocele\u003C/strong\u003E is a dilatation of the pampiniform plexus veins within the scrotum. These present as scrotal rather than groin swellings, have a characteristic \u0027bag of worms\u0027 feel on examination, and would not reach the size suggested by the clinical image. Additionally, varicoceles typically present in younger men.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Inguinoscrotal hernias are long-standing indirect inguinal hernias that have descended through the inguinal canal into the scrotum.","The characteristic presentation is a groin swelling that becomes more prominent on standing and may extend into the scrotum.","Femoral hernias extend inferiorly along the thigh rather than into the scrotum due to the anatomical direction of the femoral canal."],"references":["Pelly T, Hwang R, Nirmalan P, et l. Inguinal and femoral hernias. BMJ2024;386:e079531 http://dx.doi.org/10.1136/bmj-2024-079531"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93192"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22641"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22015"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22015"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aVmUt6B3PfUHXmVJjFTL2sf0qgpxO0.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/aVmUt6B3PfUHXmVJjFTL2sf0qgpxO0.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":330,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93192"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-08T09:04:56+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-13T11:25:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15588"}},"content